lines.value: great britain stretches over approximately ten degrees of latitude on its longer north south axis
lines.name: Yiddish

lines.value: geographically the island is marked by low rolling countryside in the east and south while hills and mountains predominate in the western and northern regions
lines.name: Yiddish

lines.value: before the end of the last ice age great britain was a peninsula of europe the rising sea levels caused by glacial melting at the end of the ice age caused the formation of the english channel the body of water which now separates great britain from continental europe at a minimum distance of 21 miles 34 km
lines.name: Yiddish

lines.value: politically great britain describes the combination of england scotland and wales and therefore also includes a number of outlying islands such as the isle of wight anglesey the isles of scilly the hebrides and the island groups of orkney and shetland but does not include other outlying islands such as the isle of man or the channel islands
lines.name: Yiddish

lines.value: great britain has evolved politically from the gradual union of england and scotland which started in 1603 with the union of crowns under james vi of scotland and eventually resulted in the acts of union in 1707 which merged the parliaments of each nation and thus resulted in the formation of the kingdom of great britain which covered the entire island to the situation following 1801 in which great britain together with the island of ireland constituted the larger united kingdom of great britain and ireland uk
lines.name: Yiddish

lines.value: the uk became the united kingdom of great britain and northern ireland in 1922 following the independence of five sixths of ireland as first the irish free state a dominion of the then british commonwealth and then later as an independent republic outside the british commonwealth as the republic of ireland
lines.name: Yiddish

lines.value: the island of great britain was first inhabited by people who crossed over the land bridge from the european mainland
lines.name: Yiddish

lines.value: its iron age inhabitants are known as the brythons a group speaking a celtic language and most of it not the northernmost part was conquered to become the ancient roman province of britannia
lines.name: Yiddish

lines.value: after the fall of the roman empire the brythons of the south and east of the island became assimilated by colonising germanic tribes angles saxons and jutes who became known as the english people
lines.name: Yiddish

lines.value: beyond hadrian's wall the major ethnic groups were the scots who may have emigrated from ireland and the picts as well as other brythonic peoples in the south west
lines.name: Yiddish

lines.value: the south east of scotland was colonised by the angles and formed until 1018 a part of the kingdom of northumbria
lines.name: Yiddish

lines.value: to speakers of germanic languages the brythons were called welsh a term that came eventually to be applied exclusively to the inhabitants of what is now wales but which survives also in names like wallace
lines.name: Yiddish

lines.value: in subsequent centuries vikings settled in several parts of the island and the norman conquest introduced a french ruling elite who also became assimilated
lines.name: Yiddish

lines.value: since the union of 1707 the entire island has been one political unit firstly as the kingdom of great britain later as part of the united kingdom of great britain and ireland and then as part of the present united kingdom of great britain and northern ireland
lines.name: Yiddish

lines.value: since the formation of this unified state the adjective british has come to refer to things associated with the united kingdom generally such as citizenship and not the island of great britain
lines.name: Yiddish

lines.value: the term was used officially for the first time during the reign of king james vi of scotland i of england
lines.name: Yiddish

lines.value: though england and scotland each remained legally in existence as separate countries with their own parliaments on 20 october 1604 king james proclaimed himself as king of great brittaine france and ireland a title that continued to be used by many of his successors
lines.name: Yiddish

lines.value: in 1707 an act of union joined both parliaments
lines.name: Yiddish

lines.value: that act used two different terms to describe the new all island nation a united kingdom and the kingdom of great britain
lines.name: Yiddish

lines.value: however the former term is regarded by many as having been a description of the union rather than its formal name at that stage
lines.name: Yiddish

lines.value: most reference books therefore describe the all island kingdom that existed between 1707 and 1800 as the kingdom of great britain
lines.name: Yiddish

lines.value: in 1801 under a new act of union this kingdom merged with the kingdom of ireland over which the monarch of great britain had ruled
lines.name: Yiddish

lines.value: the new kingdom was from then onwards unambiguously called the united kingdom of great britain and ireland
lines.name: Yiddish

lines.value: in 1922 26 of ireland's 32 counties attained independence to form a separate irish free state
lines.name: Yiddish

lines.value: the remaining truncated kingdom has therefore since then been known as the united kingdom of great britain and northern ireland
lines.name: Yiddish

lines.value: great britain is often used to mean the united kingdom of great britain and northern ireland uk
lines.name: Yiddish

lines.value: however great britain is only the largest island within the united kingdom which includes numerous surrounding smaller islands as well as northern ireland in the island of ireland
lines.name: Yiddish

lines.value: in the introduction to his history book the isles norman davies explains how confusion persists about what great britain and the united kingdom actually denote in even some eminent educational institutions
lines.name: Yiddish

lines.value: terms associated with great britain - such as britain or british - are generally used as short forms for the united kingdom or its citizens respectively
lines.name: Yiddish

lines.value: great britain and its abbreviations gb and gbr are used in some international codes as a synonym for the united kingdom largely due to potential confusion with ua or ukr for ukraine
lines.name: Yiddish

lines.value: examples include universal postal union the international olympic committee international sports teams nato the international organization for standardization and other organisations
lines.name: Yiddish

lines.value: see also country codes international licence plate codes and technical standards such as the iso 3166 geocodes gb and gbr

lines.value: the name britain is derived from the name britannia used by the romans from circa 55 bc and increasingly used to describe the island which had formerly been known as insula albionum the island of the albions
lines.name: Yiddish

lines.value: albion alouion in ptolemy is sometimes used now to refer to england specifically
lines.name: Yiddish

lines.value: occasionally it refers to scotland which is called alba in gaelic albain in irish and yr alban in welsh
lines.name: Yiddish

lines.value: pliny the elder in his natural history iv.xvi.102 applies it unequivocally to great britain
lines.name: Yiddish

lines.value: the name britannia derived from the travel writings of the ancient greek pytheas around 320 bc which described various islands in the north atlantic as far north as thule probably iceland)
lines.name: Yiddish

lines.value: although pytheas own writings do not survive later greek writers described the islands as the ai bpettaviai or the brittanic isles
lines.name: Yiddish

lines.value: the peoples of these islands of prettanike were called the npettavoi priteni or pretani
lines.name: Yiddish

lines.value: these names derived from a celtic name which is likely to have reached pytheas from the gauls who may have used it as their term for the inhabitants of the islands
lines.name: Yiddish

lines.value: priteni is the source of the welsh language term prydain britain which has the same source as the goidelic term cruithne used to refer to the early brythonic speaking inhabitants of ireland and the north of scotland
lines.name: Yiddish

lines.value: the latter were later called picts or caledonians by the romans
lines.name: Yiddish

lines.value: during roman times the term britannia was applied to the roman province of britain which occupied most of the island of great britain and to the island as a whole
lines.name: Yiddish

lines.value: see british isles terminology for further discussion of etymology
lines.name: Yiddish

lines.value: great britain may well be a translation of the french term grande bretagne which is used in france to distinguish britain from brittany in french bretagne which had been settled in late roman times by romano celtic troops from maximus army and later by refugees from roman britain who were then under attack by the anglo saxons
lines.name: Yiddish

lines.value: since the english court and aristocracy was largely french speaking for about two centuries after the norman conquest of 1066 the french term may have naturally passed into english usage
lines.name: Yiddish

lines.value: the term bretayne the grete was used by chroniclers as early as 1338 but it was not used officially until james i proclaimed himself king of great britain on 20 october 1604 to avoid the more cumbersome title king of england and scotland
lines.name: Yiddish

lines.value: sources such as the new oxford american dictionary noad define great britain as england wales and scotland considered as a unit and britain as an island that consists of england wales and scotland thus britain is the name of the island while great britain is the name of the geopolitical unit
lines.name: Yiddish

lines.value: noad advises that while britain is broadly synonymous with great britain the longer form is usual for the political unit however in the united kingdom itself britain is usually taken to be synonymous with the united kingdom of great britain and northern ireland
lines.name: Yiddish

lines.value: in geoffrey of monmouth's pseudohistorical historia regum britanniae circa 1136 the island of great britain was referred to as britannia major greater britain to distinguish it from britannia minor lesser britain the continental region which approximates to modern brittany
lines.name: Yiddish

lines.value: in irish wales is referred to as an bhreatain bheag which means literally little britain although a truer translation would be britain minor
lines.name: Yiddish

lines.value: on the other hand the closely related language scottish gaelic uses the term a'bhreatainn bheag to refer to brittany
lines.name: Yiddish

lines.value: little britain is also the name of a bbc radio and television sketch show and the name of streets in the city of london and in dorchester
lines.name: Yiddish

lines.value: the street in london was named in honour of the former embassy of the duchy of brittany which was located there
